                <ab>
                    <lb n="1"/><persName type="divine" ref="#Eumenis"><name nymRef="#Εὐμενίς"><expan><abbr>Εὐμε</abbr><ex>νίδων</ex></expan></name></persName> 
                    <persName type="attested"><name nymRef="#Κλη_"><abbr>Κλη</abbr></name></persName>
	 </ab>
            </div><div type="apparatus" xml:space="preserve">
            
                <p/>
 </div><div type="translation" xml:lang="fr" xml:space="preserve">
            <p><supplied reason="subaudible">Autel</supplied> des Euménides. <abbr>Klè</abbr>.</p>
         </div><div type="translation" xml:lang="en" xml:space="preserve">
            <p><supplied reason="subaudible">Altar</supplied> of the Eumenides. <abbr>Kle</abbr>.</p>
         </div><div type="translation" xml:lang="it" xml:space="preserve">
            <p><supplied reason="subaudible">Altare</supplied> delle Eumenidi. <abbr>Kle</abbr>.</p>
         </div><div type="commentary">
                
                <p>For the context, see commentary at <ref type="inscription" source="#IGCyr2">IGCyr064600</ref>.</p>
	       <p><foreign xml:lang="grc">Κλη</foreign> was not explained either by †Oliverio nor by Pugliese Carratelli. It is probably the abbreviated name of the owner of this 'private' altar.</p>
	<p/>
            </div></body>
